berg (1567-1636?) is the anonymous author of the "EselKönig" ("King Ass") (1625), the most vitriolic known satire against Rosicrucians, Pansophists and Paracelsists, movements which gained considerable currency in the early 17th century. The present study examines Spangenberg's motives and objectives and relates the "EselKönig" to his earlier satirical writings "Des Flohes Strauß mit der Lauß" ("The Flea's Combat with the Louse"), "Lob der Mucken" ("In Praise of Gnats"), and "GanßKönig" ("King Goose").  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aSatire. 4aSpangenberg, Wolfhart. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies - 1990 - 1999z9783110637830oZDB-23-GLC0 cprintz978348432094940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311093644540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110936445423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110936445/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GLCc1990d1999